Date: 10 May 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Canada.com [29 Apr 2005] [edited]
<http://www.canada.com/health/story.html?id=28cc66e0-c833-4aaf-a22f-8e7472fafbca>

Ontario reports large rubella outbreak, warns could be tip of iceberg
-----------------------
Public health officials in Ontario reported a large outbreak of rubella,
sometimes known as German measles, on Friday [29 Apr 2005] and warned the
50 cases that have currently been confirmed could be the tip of the iceberg.
Dr Sheela Basrur, the province's chief medical officer of health,
confirmed the cluster centres on a school in the Woodstock region in Oxford
County, but has spilled into the neighbouring counties of Brant and
Norfolk. The known cases are mainly young children at this point, she said
in an interview from Kingston.
"The cases appear to be linked to the Dutch Reform Church which tends to
avoid immunization for religious reasons," Basrur said. "Therefore we have
a highly susceptible population that are unimmunized against common
childhood diseases, including German measles."
[byline: Helen Branswell]
