[Rubella is a vaccine-preventable disease, still endemic in many countries
(see below -- a total of 10 prior postings on rubella in over 10 years of
ProMED-mail's existence). However, this outbreak has too many "deja vu"
components to allow this moderator to follow our policy of not posting
"routine" outbreaks of vaccine-preventable diseases -- and definitely
serves as a reminder that we live in a global village.
In 1978/1979, the last outbreak of polio in Canada and the USA was related
to travel between the Netherlands (where the outbreak was ongoing in 1978)
and Canada by members of the Reformed Netherlands Congregation, a religious
group that refused vaccinations based on religious beliefs. The following
quote is from a MMWR article originally published on 27 Jul 1979 and
contributed to by this moderator at that time: "Epidemiologic information
also links last year's [1978] poliomyelitis epidemic in the Netherlands and
Canada with this year's outbreak in the United States and Canada. During
the 1978 outbreak, members of the affected religious group traveled from
the Netherlands to Canada, where cases subsequently appeared. An Amish
family from an Ontario town [near Woodstock] 15 miles from the affected
area moved in late summer 1978 to the Pennsylvania town where the 1st U.S.
Amish case subsequently occurred, in January 1979. There were also other,
less well-defined contacts between Amish persons in Ontario and
Pennsylvania." <http://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/00050435.htm>
Genetic markers performed on the viruses involved in all 3 countries were
similar to those of a poliovirus circulating in Kuwait in 1977.
This current outbreak of rubella seems to be following a similar geographic
journey, thus far restricted to the same religious subgroup that places
constraints on vaccination of its children. Further similarities include
the recent declaration of interruption of rubella transmission in the USA
(see Achievements in public health: elimination of rubella and congenital
rubella syndrome -- United States, 1969--2004. 2005; 54(early release):1-4,
21 Mar <http://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/mm54e321a1.htm>). One
wonders if the virus will follow the same itinerary -- to other neighboring
groups that do not vaccinate based on religious beliefs and then south into
the USA.
Returning to rubella, for the individual infected, it is usually a mild
self-limited febrile rash illness with minimal sequelae. It has been
associated with a self-limited poly-arthritis/arthropathy, especially in
adult women (up to 70 per cent of adult women may manifest this).
Encephalitis has been reported at a rate of 1 in 6000 infections, again
more frequent in adult women. Hemorrhagic manifestations have been reported
at a rate of 1 in 3000 infections, felt to be due to low platelets and
vascular damage, more common in children than adults, and most cases
recover. The more serious consequences of infection with this virus occur
when a pregnant woman is infected, producing a complex of multiple
congenital anomalies in the child, referred to as congenital rubella
syndrome. When infection occurs in early gestation, it may lead to fetal
death, spontaneous abortion, or premature delivery. While fetal infection
may occur throughout pregnancy, defects are rare when infection occurs
after the 20th week of gestation.
In the pre-vaccine era, serosurveys conducted in the USA revealed that by
age 18, about 85 per cent of the population had evidence of prior rubella
infection, leaving about 15 per cent of the population over age 18 (and
thereby in the childbearing age group) susceptible.
Rubella virus was first isolated in 1962 by Parkman and Weller. Rubella
virus is classified as a togavirus, genus Rubivirus, and is most closely
related to group A arboviruses, such as Eastern and Western Equine
Encephalitis viruses. It is an enveloped RNA virus, with a single antigenic
type that does not cross-react with other members of the togavirus group.
(The above background information includes information from the Pink Book
on vaccine preventible diseases chapter on rubella found at:
<http://www.cdc.gov/nip/publications/pink/rubella.pdf>). - Mod.MPP]
